{"id":"2304.11497","submitter":"Vikas Srivastava","authors":"Sijun Niu, Venkatsai Bellala, Daanish A. Qureshi, Vikas Srivastava","title":"A machine learning method to characterize the crack length and position\n  in high-density polyethylene using ultrasound","comments":"19 pages, 8 figures, under peer review","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci cond-mat.soft","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  High-density polyethylene (HDPE) is a semi-crystalline polymer used in\nseveral critical applications, ranging from cooling water pipelines in nuclear\npower plants and natural gas and hydrogen pipelines to biomedical implants.\nEmbedded crack-like flaws form within HDPE during fabrication or operations.\nNon-visible flaws grow over time and can cause catastrophic failure if\nundetected. There is a lack of a non-destructive evaluation methodology that\ncan rapidly and accurately predict embedded crack length and position\nsimultaneously in large HDPE structures. Ultrasonic A-scan non-destructive\ntesting (NDT) allows for the rapid scan of large structures. Current NDT\nmethods rely on technical experts to evaluate the ultrasound measurements,\nwhich leads to high uncertainty and errors as the quantitative information\nabout a crack is subtly encoded in the reflected signal. An optimally trained\nmachine learning model can decipher the crack characteristics, but a lack of\nlarge, well-distributed, and labeled datasets to train machine learning models\ncontinues to be a major limitation. We have conducted computer simulations of\nultrasound on HDPE to develop training data. We show that a fully finite\nelement simulations trained convolutional neural network (CNN) can accurately\npredict crack lengths and positions in HDPE from experimentally measured\nultrasound A-scan signals, with an average error of 3.2% for the crack lengths\nand 3.8% for the crack positions. Our method is based on fast acquired 1D time\namplitude signal and not based on 2D image analysis as the image rendering NDT\nis very slow and susceptible to losing subtle crack features information during\nthe post-processing to create images. The proposed methodology presents a\npathway for training CNN using computationally-generated data and applying the\ntrained CNN to the field to quantify hidden cracks in large HDPE or other\npolymer structures.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 22 Apr 2023 23:17:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-25"}
